{"id":"2012.05130","submitter":"Wenting Cheng","authors":"Wenting Cheng, Emil Prodan, Camelia Prodan","title":"Revealing the boundary Weyl physics of the four-dimensional Hall effect\n  via phason engineering in metamaterials","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevApplied.16.044032","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Quantum Hall physics has been theoretically predicted in 4-dimensions and\nhigher. In hypothetical 2n-dimensions, the topological characters of both the\nbulk and the boundary are manifested as quantized non-linear transport\ncoefficients that connect, respectively, to the n-th Chern number of the bulk\ngap projection and to the n-th winding number of the Weyl spectral\nsingularities on the (2n-1)-dimensional boundaries. Here, we introduce the\nconcept of phason engineering in metamaterials and use it as a vehicle to\naccess and apply the quantum Hall physics in arbitrary dimensions. Using these\nspecialized design principles, we fabricate a re-configurable 2-dimensional\naperiodic acoustic crystal with a phason living on a 2-torus, giving us access\nto the 4-dimensional quantum Hall physics. Also, we supply a direct\nexperimental confirmation that the topological boundary spectrum assembles in a\nWeyl singularity when mapped as function of the quasi-momenta. We also\ndemonstrate topological wave steering enabled by the Weyl physics of the\n3-dimensional boundaries.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Dec 2020 16:08:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 15 May 2021 18:52:53 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 19 Oct 2021 20:48:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-22"}
